ce:section.ce:para:
The chlorophyll-derived multi-color CPDs could be successfully obtained through a hydrothermal method only by adjusting the temperature or time of the reaction (Fig.1
                        ). Specifically, red-emitted CPDs (red-CPDs) can be first prepared at the condition of 130 °C 3 h. Then with the reaction time and temperature increased respectively, white-emitted CPDs (white-CPDs) and blue-emitted CPDs (blue-CPDs) were obtained. As shown in the inset images of Fig.2
                        A-C, the synthesized aqueous solution appeared transparent light yellowish green to pale yellow, and when under illumination by 365 nm ultraviolet (UV) radiation, the samples displayed red, white and blue fluorescence respectively. Fig.2E showed the fluorescence spectra (with the intensity normalized) of three CPDs under their optimal excitation. Correspondingly, the Commission International d’Eclairage (CIE) coordinate of red-CPDs was located at (0.52, 0.35), white-CPDs was at (0.34, 0.32) and blue-CPDs was at (0.16, 0.19), therein the CIE coordinate of white-CPDs was close to standard white light (0.33, 0.33) (Fig.2F). In detail, the fluorescence spectra (Fig.2A-C) showed that all three kinds of CPDs exhibited an emission around 440-510 nm with an excitation wavelength-dependent behavior, which might be ascribed to the surface states [33]. Whereas red-CPDs and white-CPDs presented triple emission property (Fig.2A-B), the other two emissions at about 603 and 658 nm were excitation-independent, which implied a probable fluorescence mechanism of molecular state or crosslink-enhanced emission effect (CEE) [34,35].

To evaluate the precision of hemin detection by white-CPDs, triplicate experiments were performed. It was found that the fluorescence intensity at 658 nm was closely related to the concentration of hemin. Accordingly, a standard curve was obtained with good linear relationship (R2=0.9963) over the range of 0.1-0.95 μM (Fig.6B). The detection limit estimated basing on the equation 3σ/k was 0.043 μM, where σ is the standard deviation of 11 blank measurements and k is the slope of the linear calibration plot. Besides, the inset photographs in Fig.6B showed a clear change in the fluorescence color of CPDs from white to blue with the concentration of hemin went up. Considering the complexity of the blood system, it was necessary to study the selectivity of this analytical method for hemin detection. Herein, several common biological molecules and ions were selected as potential interference components (each at a concentration of 50 μM), and the fluorescence intensity of the treated white-CPDs solution at 658 nm was investigated. As demonstrated in Fig.7
                        , the red bars showed the response of white-CPDs’ fluorescence only in the presence of each interfering component, while the blue bars showed the fluorescence response with the coexistence of above interfering components and hemin (0.5 μM). It was clearly observed that all these substances alone brought no obvious changes in the fluorescence emission of white-CPDs, while the fluorescence intensity of the competition experiments maintained the comparable level of that white-CPDs interacted merely with hemin. Therefore, this methodology showed well sensitivity and selectivity comparing with the previous reported methods for the determination of hemin (Table 1
                        ), and could satisfied the requirements for hemin detection in complex solutions.

The practical application of white-CPDs based fluorescence sensing system for hemin detection was then explored. After pretreated according to the method mentioned above, serum samples spiked with standard hemin solutions were measured. The results in Table 2
                         presented that the recoveries of these samples varied from 99.02 to 102.03% and the relative standard deviations (RSD) were below 4.04%, which were acceptable in most cases. Moreover, the spiked serum samples (with 2-fold volume of acetonitrile added to remove the contained proteins for preventing the column blocked) were also tested according to a reported liquid chromatography (LC) method for the detection of hemin [55]. The obtained recoveries of three samples were 97.35-107.41% with the RSD of 4.42-14.9% (Table 3
                        ). Obviously, the CPDs-based fluorescence sensing system possessed reasonable dependability and stability in terms of quantification comparing with the LC method (Tables 2-3).
